Subject:    Question about structure of domain names
From:       <a href="?a=95837816800017&r=1&w=2">twwells!bill () uunet ! uu ! net  (T !  William Wells)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=199002">1990-02-11 2:44:55</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326864&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326864&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Well, I'm hoping this is the right newsgroup. Here's my questions:
I have this program that sifts through my newsfeed looking for
domain names (among other things). Not being a domain name expert,
I've guessed that the format for a domain name is
[-_+a-zA-Z0-9]+(\.[-_+a-zA-Z0-9])+ with the last part being from a
restricted set.

This is insufficiently specific; for example, it often gets things
with components that are entirely numeric. It occured to me that
such things might be ill-formed, in which case I could just ignore
them.

So what are the rules for forming domain names?

Two points: it may be that this is adequately answered in an RFC
somewhere. If so, feel free to tell me the RFC number; I can RTFM
if I know which FM it's in! Also, one answer would be: try to
connect to it and see if it works. True. But since I'm not even on
the Internet, that's *expensive*. So I want to filter out as many
names as possible before I actually do the query.

(Why do I care if I'm not on the Internet? I moderate
comp.archives and am looking for postings of anonymous FTP
archives. Yes, I do have ways to get to the Internet but they are
all long distance calls.)

I don't read this newsgroup so please e-mail your responses. If
there is any interest, I'll post a summary.

---
Bill                    { uunet | novavax | ankh } !twwells!bill
bill@twwells.com

